comments.body:
@BrucePay 
> I don't know - maybe we should make you add `using module` statements for cmdlets that aren't part of the PowerShell core.

Lets say I have the following `MyModule.psm1`:

```powershell
Enum MyEnum {
    A
    B
}

class MyClass {
    [MyEnum]$Prop1

    MyClass () {
        $This.Prop1 = Get-MyEnumPrivate
    }
}

function Get-MyClassPublic {
    [CmdletBinding()]
    [OutputType([MyClass])]
    param ()
    end {
        [MyClass]::New()
    }
}
Export-ModuleMember -Function Get-MyClassPublic

function Get-MyEnumPrivate {
    [CmdletBinding()]
    [OutputType([MyEnum])]
    param ()
    end {
        [MyEnum]::B
    }
}
```

If checking for unresolved commands and compile time resulted in an error, would that mean module authors would now need to ensure the private functions a method consumes exists or is defined before the class is compiled? That would seem troubling.
